Subsidy Snares
CAMBRIDGE – No policy pitting good economics against good politics more directly than food and energy subsidies.
Unaffordable subsidies have become core issues for three of the world’s most important new leaders: Egyptian President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, Indonesian President Joko “Jokowi” Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi.
El-Sisi faces a reduction in subsidies that is slightly better than anticipated.
By contrast, Modi faces a much worse situation, even risking the collapse of the long-awaited World Trade Organization agreement.
And the situation Jokowi faces remains unclear.
In July, Sisi achieved what few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East have been able to do: he significantly reduced long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41-78%.
Surprisingly, there was little opposition to his actions.
Egypt’s food subsidy program alone costs over $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices had remained at extremely low levels, often used for animal feed.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often sparked unrest and even overthrew governments.
But the Sisi government seems to be making progress on this front as well.
Bread subsidies have been reduced by 13%.
Sisi had no choice.
Even after the cuts, the current government’s budget deficit target for the next fiscal year is 10% of GDP (it would be 14% without the cuts).
But few expected Sisi, who took office in a tumultuous political environment, to act more quickly than Modi. Modi became prime minister in India, which was eager for comprehensive economic reform, with an overwhelming democratic mandate.
In Indonesia, Jokowi, who took office in October, inherited fuel subsidies worth $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20% of government spending), which had already become a burden on the nation.
Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono took a brave first step a year ago by increasing fuel prices.
Jokowi’s advisors recommended cutting the remaining subsidies, and he candidly stated his plan to phase them out over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies because agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with large numbers of consumers on the demand side and producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive markets, it is governments – not large private monopolies – that are the problem.
Critics of the invisible hand argue that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are two main reasons for government intervention.
Food and fossil fuel subsidies are particularly controversial because they often claim to serve environmental or equity goals, but in reality, they often do little to achieve these objectives and can even be counterproductive.
Only about 20% of Egypt’s food subsidies go to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies enrich the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies went to the poorest people, while 52.6% flowed into the pockets of the richest.
Worldwide, fewer than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies go to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy; the Modi government, which sought to protect agricultural subsidies in India, is a case in point.
In fact, the Modi government vetoed the WTO compromise, thereby destroying the most significant advance in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade.
Agricultural subsidies can benefit consumers at the expense of producers, especially in poor countries; or benefit producers at the expense of consumers, especially in rich countries.
India's policy aims to do both.
The result is a feat for India: providing wheat to consumers at artificially low prices while experiencing overproduction because farmers can get high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs – electricity, water, and fertilizer – which leads to environmental damage.
) The government acquires large amounts of corrupt rice and wheat, and the small portion available to consumers is distributed in a corrupt manner and fails to help the poor.
The government may continue to provide subsidies and storage reserves.
But it knows that this would violate World Trade Organization rules.
Since the rules cannot be permanently changed, Modi simply rejected the Trade Facilitation Agreement, which the WTO had eagerly awaited.
Once subsidies are implemented, it will be difficult to undo them.
When world commodity prices rise (as they have over the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot shield them from shocks.
But people accustomed to fixed food and energy prices will demand that the government take responsibility.
This constitutes a strong argument against implementing subsidies in the first place.
This does not mean, however, that keeping subsidies in place would always be the shrewd politician's best choice once they are implemented.
If the alternative to higher prices is shortages or rationing, angry opponents could erupt.
Similarly, if growing disparities eventually lead to higher retail prices, slow-moving leaders would not benefit either.
In an ideal scenario, reducing food and energy subsidies should be accompanied by other more effective measures to support low-income households.
Developing countries have already learned much about effective transfer mechanisms, such as conditional cash transfer policies like Progresa-Oportunidades in Mexico and Bolsa Família in Brazil, as well as technological innovations like India's Unique Identification system.
But some countries may only be forced to adjust when budget crises hit, leaving them without the funds needed for transfers to alleviate suffering.
Clever politicians might implement unpopular adjustments early in their tenure.
Both Jokowi and Xi have followed this approach.
And Modi, who won elections on a platform of market reforms, has fallen behind.
